    <item>
      <title>Haptic</title>
      <link>https://antoine.weill-duflos.fr/en/slides/haptic/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 30 Oct 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://antoine.weill-duflos.fr/en/slides/haptic/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;designing-haptic-interactions&#34;&gt;Designing haptic interactions&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;aside class=&#34;notes&#34;&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;We often underestimate how important the sense of touch is in our daily interactions.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s the first sense baby develops.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you think about the other senses, they are very localized, but touched is all around !&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/aside&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;a-bit-of-taxonomy&#34;&gt;A bit of Taxonomy&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Somatosensory systems&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Somesthetic senses:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;sense of touch&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;proprioception&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;haptic perception&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;span class=&#34;fragment &#34; &gt;
Haptic feedback
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;
    - &lt;span class=&#34;fragment &#34; &gt;
  Kinesthetic
&lt;/span&gt;
    - &lt;span class=&#34;fragment &#34; &gt;
  Tactile
&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;aside class=&#34;notes&#34;&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;When we say «touch» we may actually refer to different things, is the pain felt the same way as cold ? Do we feel force with the same mechanisms as we feel the softness of a blanket ?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Let&amp;rsquo;s talk about how everything works, but first let&amp;rsquo;s introduce some words.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The somatosensory system is a part of the sensory nervous system, it responds to changes at the surface or inside of the body.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The somatic senses or somesthetic senses are the sense of touch, proprioception (sense of position and movement) and haptic perception. Haptic perception is often associated with active touch.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And because that&amp;rsquo;s not enough term, engineer often talks about Haptic feedback being divided in kinesthetic and tactile.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Still following ? lets try to get into how it works.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/aside&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;types-of-tactile-receptors&#34;&gt;Types of tactile receptors&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Mechanoreceptors&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Thermoreceptors&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Nociceptors&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;span class=&#34;fragment &#34; &gt;
  All sharing the same channel
&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class=&#34;fragment &#34; &gt;
  Gate Control Theory
&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class=&#34;fragment &#34; &gt;
  running cool water on a burned area = less pain
&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;aside class=&#34;notes&#34;&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Tactile receptors are cells reacting to tactile stimilus, they can be divide in thre types.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Interestingly they sort of use the same channel to convey the information to the brain.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This create an effect called gating, information are competing to get to the brain.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And that&amp;rsquo;s a why running your finger under cool water diminish the pain sensation associated with a burn.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/aside&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;tactile-receptors&#34;&gt;Tactile receptors&lt;/h2&gt;
















&lt;figure  &gt;
  &lt;div class=&#34;d-flex justify-content-center&#34;&gt;
    &lt;div class=&#34;w-100&#34; &gt;&lt;img alt=&#34;&#34; srcset=&#34;
               /en/slides/haptic/tactilereceptors_huc935bc54a0d7734c1763f932ee1df6a6_291499_4bc8f666e6b0f32d5771e79a26d7a176.webp 400w,
               /en/slides/haptic/tactilereceptors_huc935bc54a0d7734c1763f932ee1df6a6_291499_acb8c1f81aaedf86d2a2632887d0079a.webp 760w,
               /en/slides/haptic/tactilereceptors_huc935bc54a0d7734c1763f932ee1df6a6_291499_1200x1200_fit_q90_h2_lanczos_3.webp 1200w&#34;
               src=&#34;https://antoine.weill-duflos.fr/en/slides/haptic/tactilereceptors_huc935bc54a0d7734c1763f932ee1df6a6_291499_4bc8f666e6b0f32d5771e79a26d7a176.webp&#34;
